column1: A solid purchase
column2: but a few flaws	"I just purchased and assembled this desk to replace a worn-out desk of similar quality. Here's some notes for those who are considering the same:

column1: * Shipping was fast. The desk shipped within 24 hours from CA. Since I'm in AZ it arrived only a few days later. The desk was packed in 2 boxes
column2: which arrived one day apart. Not surprisingly the boxes are big and heavy
column3: about 65lb and 85lb each. You'll definitely need a dolly or a couple strong people to help move them from your doorstep. The boxes themselves were damaged in transit
column4: but the liberal use of styrofoam (yuck) prevented any damage inside.

column1: * The instructions consisted of diagrams with minimal words. However the steps were mostly understandable and words were used to point out especially critical steps when the diagram wasn't clear enough.  Some steps were still vague however
column2: requiring extra scrutiny or trial-and-error. All parts were clearly labeled and several spares of each screw and nut were generously included.

column1: * The 45-steps took several hours to complete as not a single piece was pre-assembled. Having a helper insert dowels
column2: screws or assemble drawers while you work on the major steps will save a lot of time. Also an electric screwdriver with a phillips and hex head will save a LOT of effort! Thankfully no other tools are required.

column1: * Be sure to assemble the desk in the same room where it will be placed. The 2 sides are not designed to separate
column2: and once assembled it is semi-permanent. Also be aware the cabinet on the left and the drawers on the right are NOT reversible
column3: the pre-drilled holes do not allow for any option besides what is shown.

column1: * For some inexplicable reason
column2: several locknuts and screws are located on the outside of the desk so they are clearly visible. They could have easily been placed on the other side which would have hidden them under the desktop
column3: but the manufacturer must assume this desk will be placed in a corner with both outer sides against the wall. At least small matching stickers are included to hide the some (but not all) of the holes
column4: but it still looks unattractive if any outer side is visible to the room.

column1: * For pre-fab
column2: engineered wood furniture this desk is pretty sturdy. The wood plates are thick and heavy
column3: and the joined pieces are highly reinforced. For example there over 28 locknuts and screws securing the desktop to the body.  The drawers are solid and slide easily and appear they could hold a lot of weight.

column1: * The cabinet does not have any holes or perforations on the back panel. If you plan on placing a PC or other electric equipment inside
column2: you'll have to cut a wiring hole yourself.

column1: * The black surface of the desk looks nice
column2: especially compared to the faux-woodgrain design of other cheap furniture
column3: but it seems every speck of dust and fingerprint is obvious. It's likely the surface will never look pristine!

column1: Overall I'm happy with my purchase. There are some flaws and room for improvement
column2: but I feel like I got my money worth. This isn't something you'll pass on to your grandkids
column3: but its certainly good enough to write this review on!"	4	4	https://www.amazon.com/gp/customer-reviews/RR4XJEH328EYT/ref=cm_cr_getr_d_rvw_ttl?ie=UTF8&ASIN=B0D7M9BKQY	1/23/2025	ç‰©æµé€Ÿåº¦	åŒ…è£…ä¿æŠ¤æ€§	å®‰è£…è¯´æ˜ä¹¦å†…å®¹	ä½¿ç”¨å™ªéŸ³	æŠ½å±‰æ‰¿é‡èƒ½åŠ›	ç¾è§‚åº¦	æ¬è¿éš¾åº¦	å®‰è£…æ—¶é•¿	å®‰è£…éš¾åº¦	æŸœé—¨å¼€åˆé¡ºç•…åº¦	æ¡Œé¢é˜²æ°´æ€§	çº¿ç¼†ç®¡ç†	è€è„æ€§		{'å¥½è¯„ç‚¹1': 'ç‰©æµé€Ÿåº¦'
